    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-09-16T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-09-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="8"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d8">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <persName corresp="#p_HICKERSONJD1">Hickerson</persName>–<persName
                        corresp="#p_MURPHYRD1">Murphy</persName>–<persName corresp="#p_KEYDMK1"
                        >Key</persName> files, lot 58 D 33, “US–<gloss target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss>
                    talks—September 1952”</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Draft of Part I of Three-Part Agenda for United States–United
                        Kingdom Talks on the United Nations</hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d8fn1">Prepared in the Bureau of United Nations Affairs.
                        Regarding the items in Parts II and III of the projected agenda, see
                        bracketed note on <ref target="#pg_31">p. 31</ref>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-09-16">September 16,
                            1952</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Part</hi> I</p>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">the <gloss target="#t_UN1">un</gloss> in the political and
                        security field</hi>
                </p>
                <p rend="flushleft">A. <hi rend="italic">Objectives and Instrumentalities:</hi>
                </p>
                <p>I. Relationship of <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> collective security
                    activities to <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> pacific settlement
                    functions.</p>
                <pb facs="0042" n="14" xml:id="pg_14"/>
                <list>
                    <label>
                        <hi rend="italic">a</hi>.</label>
                    <item>What are the possibilities of, and what are the limitations on, <gloss
                            target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> action to: <list>
                            <label>(1)</label>
                            <item>achieve East-West settlement;</item>
                            <label>(2)</label>
                            <item>settle disputes not directly involving East-West conflict;</item>
                            <label>(3)</label>
                            <item>unify and strengthen the non-Communist world;</item>
                            <label>(4)</label>
                            <item>bring about change, other than by war, in the Soviet
                                system;</item>
                            <label>(5)</label>
                            <item>organize a general system of collective security.</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <label>
                        <hi rend="italic">b</hi>.</label>
                    <item>To what extent are these aims mutually exclusive?</item>
                    <label>
                        <hi rend="italic">c</hi>.</label>
                    <item>Where should greatest emphasis be placed?</item>
                </list>
                <list>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>How could <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> machinery be utilized in event
                        of: <list>
                            <label>
                                <hi rend="italic">a</hi>.</label>
                            <item>Future localized aggression (other Koreas);</item>
                            <label>
                                <hi rend="italic">b</hi>.</label>
                            <item>General war.</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Pace and scope of future efforts to strengthen <gloss target="#t_UN1"
                            >UN</gloss> in collective security field (<gloss target="#t_CMC1"
                            >CMC</gloss>).</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>Relationships between <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> and other
                        collective security arrangements: <list>
                            <label>
                                <hi rend="italic">a</hi>.</label>
                            <item>Review of present status;</item>
                            <label>
                                <hi rend="italic">b</hi>.</label>
                            <item>Desirable <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss>–<gloss
                                    target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss> relationships: <list>
                                    <label>(1)</label>
                                    <item>in peace time;</item>
                                    <label>(2)</label>
                                    <item>in case of localized aggression, in or outside <gloss
                                            target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss> area;</item>
                                    <label>(3)</label>
                                    <item>in case of general war.</item>
                                </list>
                            </item>
                            <label>
                                <hi rend="italic">c</hi>.</label>
                            <item>Desirability of further formal or informal development of <gloss
                                    target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> relationship with other regional or
                                collective defense systems.</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <label>5.</label>
                    <item>Development of <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> pacific settlement
                        functions. <list>
                            <label>
                                <hi rend="italic">a</hi>.</label>
                            <item>Use of Peace Observation Commission.</item>
                            <label>
                                <hi rend="italic">b</hi>.</label>
                            <item>Additional machinery.</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <label>6.</label>
                    <item>Role of <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> Disarmament Activities.</item>
                    <label>7.</label>
                    <item>Importance of economic and social programs, e.g.: <list>
                            <label>
                                <hi rend="italic">a</hi>.</label>
                            <item>International Development Authority;</item>
                            <label>
                                <hi rend="italic">b</hi>.</label>
                            <item>Technical Assistance Program.</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p rend="flushleft">B. <hi rend="italic">Korea—Seventh General Assembly and
                        Beyond</hi>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>General approach.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Additional measures <list>
                            <item>economic</item>
                            <item>political</item>
                            <item>military</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Post-<gloss target="#t_GA1">GA</gloss> outlook.</item>
                </list>
                <p rend="flushleft">C. <hi rend="italic">The <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> and
                        the Cold War</hi>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Attitude and probable policy of <gloss target="#t_USSR1">USSR</gloss>
                        toward the <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss>.</item>
                    <pb facs="0043" n="15" xml:id="pg_15"/>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>General posture regarding Soviet participation in <gloss target="#t_UN1"
                            >UN</gloss>: <list>
                            <label>
                                <hi rend="italic">a</hi>.</label>
                            <item>Desirability of continuing Soviet membership;</item>
                            <label>
                                <hi rend="italic">b</hi>.</label>
                            <item>Election of Soviet bloc members to <gloss target="#t_UN1"
                                    >UN</gloss> posts. (Seventh <gloss target="#t_GA1">GA</gloss>
                                examples: Successor to Czechslovakia on <gloss target="#t_ECOSOC1"
                                    >ECOSOC</gloss>; Eastern European committee
                                chairmanship).</item>
                            <label>
                                <hi rend="italic">c</hi>.</label>
                            <item>Attitude toward Soviet proposals in the <gloss target="#t_UN1"
                                    >UN</gloss>.</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Use of <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> as propaganda forum by <gloss
                            target="#t_USSR1">USSR</gloss>: East–West trade (Moscow Economic
                        Conference), Germ Warfare, etc.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>Utility of various <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> organs as propaganda
                        forums for the West.</item>
                    <label/>
                    <item>
                        <hi rend="italic">Specific problems:</hi> Austrian case; Katyn massacre;
                        Oatis, Linse, etc. cases; Swedish and U.S. plane incidents; Soviet “hate
                        America” campaign.</item>
                    <label>5.</label>
                    <item>Selectivity in determination of problems to be regraded as East-West
                        issues.</item>
                    <label>6.</label>
                    <item>Relations with “neutrals” on East–West issues.</item>
                    <label>7.</label>
                    <item>Admission of new members.</item>
                </list>
            </div>
        </body>
